EXTEND: Using built-in data and quick plots

You wouldnt fully experience learning plotting with ggplot2 if you didnt work with the diamonds data set that is built in to ggplot2. This data set contains the prices and other attributes of almost 54,000 diamonds. Since the data set is available once you load the ggplot2 package, you can use diamonds as you would any data object and R knows what you mean, as shown in the examples below. You can refer to the data set as diamonds or can assign it to a new variable if you like.

We worked with the ggplot() in our session. There is another plotting function in ggplot2 called qplot(). This was designed to allow for a quick plot. Well experiment with the qplot() below to become familiar with it.

  1. Create a qplot() that shows the relationship between price (price) and carat weight (carat) for the diamonds data set. (Use help to find out about the syntax and defaults for qplot().)

  2. Modify your code to ADD a smoothed line with error bars (created by geom smooth) to the scatterplot (geom point). (HINT: You want to combine two geoms here)

  3. Use qplot() to create a quick histogram of diamond price.

Solution

qplot(x = carat, y = price, data = diamonds) # by default if x and y supplied - will plot scatterplot (as geom = "point"), can use geom argument to change plot type.

qplot(x = carat, y = price, data = diamonds, geom = c("point","smooth"))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

qplot(x = price, data = diamonds)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

PRACTICE: Creating spectacular plots

  1. Use ggplot() to create a more sophisticated graph for the diamonds data that shows the relationship between price (price) and carat weight (carat) with coloring by the clarity rating (clarity). Adjust the transparency to better see overlapped points.

Solution

## Both options below work to generate scatterplot of price vs carat weight, colored by clarity rating:

#setting x, y variables locally (i.e., in geom_point):
ggplot(diamonds) +
  geom_point(aes(x = carat, y = price, color = clarity), alpha = 0.6) #alpha adjusts transparency - put outside of aes call to apply to all points

#setting x, y variables globally (i.e., in ggplot function call):
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = clarity), alpha = 0.6)

PRACTICE: Faceting plots

As we learned, ggplot2 has several faceting functions to divide plots into subplots based on categorical variable values.

  1. Modify the plot above: instead of coloring points by the clarity rating, create individual plots for each group using faceting. Experiment with faceting into rows, columns, or a rectangular layout to see the difference and determine which may be best for this visualization.

  2. Select your favorite version of the faceted plot and modify the scales to be free. What effect does this have on your plot?

Solution

# Facet into columns with a single row
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(~clarity)

# Facet into rows with a single column
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(clarity~.)

# Facet into rectangular layout (rows and columns)
ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~clarity, scales = "free")
